Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** that shows

* the **Lua‑facing API** you will expose to your users,
* the **C‑C++ glue** that drives the hot per‑block loop,
* a tiny **mock‑up of the BlockSci C++ iterator** (so you can compile & test the stub without the full BlockSci sources),
* a **performance‑oriented call pattern** (no extra allocations per block, minimal Lua‑C transitions, early‑exit support, and optional “no‑callback” fast‑path).

Feel free to copy‑paste the C source into a single file (e.g. `blockscilua.c`), compile it as a shared library, and drop it into your Lua `package.cpath`. The Lua side only needs the tiny wrapper shown at the end.

---

## 1. Lua‑facing API (what the user will see)

```lua
local bs = require "blockscilua"   -- the compiled library

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 1️⃣  Get an iterator over all blocks (or a range)
-- -------------------------------------------------
local it = bs.blocks()               -- iterate from genesis to tip
-- local it = bs.blocks(1000, 2000)  -- optional start/end height

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 2️⃣  Run a Lua callback for every block
-- -------------------------------------------------
-- The callback receives ONE argument: a **Block** userdata.
-- Return `false` (or nil) to stop early, `true` to continue.
it:for_each(function(block)
    -- Example: count blocks that contain at least one OP_RETURN output
    if block:has_op_return() then
        count = count + 1
    end
    return true          -- keep walking
end)

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 3️⃣  Convenience “one‑shot” API (no explicit iterator)
-- -------------------------------------------------
local n_op_return = bs.count_blocks(function(b)
    return b:has_op_return()
end)               -- returns the number of blocks that satisfied the predicate

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 4️⃣  The Block userdata (what the callback sees)
-- -------------------------------------------------
--   block:height()          -> integer
--   block:hash()            -> hex string
--   block:timestamp()       -> Unix epoch (seconds)
--   block:tx_count()        -> integer
--   block:has_op_return()   -> boolean
--   block:transactions()    -> iterator over Tx objects (omitted here)
```

### Design rationale

| Feature | Why it matters for a hot path |
|---------|------------------------------|
| **`for_each(callback)`** | The iterator owns a **single Lua reference** to the callback. No per‑block allocation, no string parsing – just a `lua_pcall` per block. |
| **Early‑exit (`return false`)** | Allows the user to stop after a few million blocks (e.g. “stop after first match”) without traversing the whole chain. |
| **Block as lightweight userdata** | The C++ `Block` object is wrapped once per block and passed as a **light userdata** inside a pre‑allocated Lua userdata; no table construction. |
| **Optional range arguments** | Users can limit the walk to a sub‑range (useful for testing). |
| **One‑shot helper (`count_blocks`)** | Mirrors the “DataFrame.apply” style of pandas/polars – a single call that internally creates an iterator, runs the callback, and returns a scalar. |
| **No GC pressure** | The `Block` userdata is **re‑used** for every iteration (the same Lua object is updated in‑place). The iterator holds the sole reference; when the iterator is GC‑collected the underlying C++ iterator is destroyed. |

