## 3.  Performance notes (what makes this hot‑path fast)

| Concern | Implementation detail |
|---------|------------------------|
| **Zero allocation per block** | The iterator holds a single `BlockUserdata*` (`iu->block_ud`). It is updated in‑place (`block = blk`). No `malloc` / `lua_newtable` per iteration. |
| **Minimal Lua stack shuffling** | The callback is fetched once (`lua_rawgeti`) and reused. The block userdata is already on the stack, so the call pattern is `push cb; push block; pcall`. |
| **Early‑exit** | The callback can return any falsy value (`nil` or `false`) to stop the walk. The loop checks `lua_toboolean` and breaks immediately – no extra work. |
| **Cache‑friendly** | The C++ iterator (`MockBlockIterator`) is a simple struct; the hot loop is a tight `while` with only a few memory accesses and a single `lua_pcall`. |
| **Error handling** | Any Lua error aborts the walk and propagates the error message unchanged (`lua_error`). This avoids hidden failures that would corrupt later analytics. |
| **Thread‑safety** | The binding is **not** thread‑safe – the iterator holds a single Lua reference. If you need parallel walks, create separate iterators in separate Lua states (or use the real BlockSci parallel APIs). |
| **JIT friendliness** | When the library is used with **LuaJIT**, the `lua_pcall` overhead is still present, but the JIT can inline the small C wrapper and keep the hot loop in native code. The only “slow” part is the Lua callback itself – exactly the same situation as `pandas.apply` or `polars.apply`. |

